    "location": "scripts/ai_agent_bridge/_cli.py:677",
    "description": "The new `--host` option accepts arbitrary bind addresses while the proxy has no authentication or authorization. Running `ab serve --openai --host 0.0.0.0` exposes local agent CLIs and the user's inherited environment-driven credentials to the network, contradicting the documented localhost-only boundary. Remote binding should require an explicit unsafe opt-in such as `--allow-remote`, or the command should reject non-loopback hosts."
  },
  {
    "id": "healthz-spawns-subprocesses",
    "severity": "MEDIUM",
    "category": "dos-surface",
    "location": "scripts/ai_agent_bridge/openai_proxy.py:257",
    "description": "`GET /healthz` runs every backend probe on each request, and each probe forks a CLI subprocess with a one-second timeout. A cheap unauthenticated endpoint can therefore create repeated `codex`, `gemini`, `claude`, and `hermes` processes, consuming CPU/process slots and tying up FastAPI workers. Health checks should use cached probe results, a lightweight static liveness response, or a separate expensive readiness endpoint."
  },
  {
    "id": "unbounded-prompt-argv",
    "severity": "MEDIUM",
    "category": "dos-surface",
    "location": "scripts/ai_agent_bridge/openai_proxy.py:154",
    "description": "Request message content is unbounded and is flattened directly into subprocess arguments for Gemini, Claude, and Hermes. Large chat requests can exceed OS argument limits, trigger repeated backend failures, consume memory during JSON parsing/prompt construction, or expose prompt contents through process listings. The proxy should enforce request size/message limits and pass prompts via stdin or temporary files instead of argv where possible."
  }
]

